    <title>Beats’ long-awaited Powerbeats Pro 2 earbuds are coming in 2025</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A marketing image of the Beats Powerbeats Pro 2." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Qc2rDSUwnLIhk84DMXb4ASXSKVE=/0x0:910x607/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73563272/Screenshot_2024_09_04_at_11.01.28_AM.0.png" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Beats&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="nzVYZ1"&gt;If there’s one product that Beats has taken its sweet time upgrading, it’s the &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/10/18563329/apple-powerbeats-pro-review-wireless-fitness-headphones-price"&gt;Powerbeats Pro&lt;/a&gt;. Released back in 2019, these wireless earbuds (and their signature ear hooks) have sat in the company’s product lineup ever since with no meaningful hardware changes. But the time has finally come for an all-new model. Today, Beats released a teaser for the Powerbeats Pro 2, which will be released sometime in 2025. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="f9u5e2"&gt;In the clip, we see the in-ear fit of the revamped design showcased by baseball sensation Shohei Ohtani. Fans of the ear hooks will be happy to see that they haven’t gone anywhere; if you want a hook-free design, Beats offers plenty of other options, including the &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/22753158/beats-fit-pro-earbuds-review-apple"&gt;Beats Fit Pro&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/23725921/beats-studio-buds-plus-earbuds-review-translucent-clear"&gt;Studio Buds Plus&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24180840/beats-solo-buds-earbuds-hands-on"&gt;Solo Buds&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
